Citations
Date: 0/0/1980
Source: Land of Munros, The
Author: NEAVE
Vol / Page: 65
Edition:
Quote:  I was to get a liberal screw and found for four months [at Otematata Station], beginning the 8th of March [1858], with... two cotton shirts ... no underclothing, no socks, but pieces of blanket rolled round your feet (we called them Prince Alberts) ... I had to make myself a cap out of a piece of an old opossum rug.
Notes: 1917 James Strachan Experiences  (Hocken L.) in 1980 Neave The Land of Munros 65

Date: 0/0/1944
Source: Shining with the Shiner
Author: LEE
Vol / Page: 71
Edition:
Quote: Just wrap around [your feet] as much Prince Albert [that is ladies' stockings] as you need, and cut the stockings off and throw the rest away.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1952
Source: Faring South
Author: LYON
Vol / Page: 180
Edition:
Quote: [The early bushman's] socks were often replaced by a long strip of calico bound from the toe upwards to a few inches above the boot top. These strips of calico were usually termed Prince Alberts.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1974
Source: Loner, The
Author: AGNEW
Vol / Page: 71
Edition:
Quote: The cocky's wife spotted my Prince Alberts, a piece of blanket cut into eighteen-inch squares which I wound over my feet. ... Prince Alberts were more serviceable than ordinary socks, were warmer, longer-wearing and would take up the slack in my boots, preventing blisters.
Notes:
